Got any questions? Ask me befikar🥰

Nope! I never took it too seriously to feel down.

If talking about #CgMethod almost no one follows it strictly considering the impractical un-scientific rules of no shampoo-no oil.

When I started following #CGmethod in 2016, I was quite sure I am not gonna break my head into it. I bought a new shampoo, a conditioner, used the same one as leave in for a long time. I just made sure they were #nosulphate #NoSilicones only to realise No-Sulphate is a trending marketing gimmick and doesn’t make much sense on its own.

Adding hair gel to my routine after one year didn’t feel difficult because by now I was quite used to styling my curly hair

#CGmethod gave me a direction to follow but I never followed it strictly.

Things that helped me continue:
-  Not giving into un-scientific fear mongering of #Nochemicals #NoParabens etc. Use what works.
- Realising it’s only silicones that sometimes buildup on my hair. Rest I can use everything if my hair likes.
- Styling after every wash in bathroom itself. Over the period it made me quicken the process for my curls.
- Now #DryItLikeDesicurly makes it even easier to speed up drying process.
- Sleeping on satin in whatever way I feel comfy. Scarf/pillow/bonnet
- Getting haircuts/trims when curls gives up on me. No emotional bond🌸
- NOT Deep Conditioning as often others are for THEIR hair
- Not heat styling/blow drying or any high temperature usage. Heat damages a lot upon prolonged use.
- Refresh curls if they look messy/dry or just bun it up😋

So basically pickup an inexpensive hair cream+a wide tooth comb and start styling your curly hair!❤️
Don’t follow any routine/method/rules just do what works for you and your lifestyle ❤️

✨Coarse VS Fine Hair - Curly Hair Routine ✨

PRODUCTS: Available and provided by @sublimelifeofficial 

Use code DESICURLY for off (affiliated)

COARSE HAIR:
• @detoxie.life Hard Water Shampoo
• @ashbabotanics Deep Treatment Hair Masque
• @fiixmycurls Curl Quenching Hair Butter
• @ashbabotanics Curl Defining Gel
• @simrasaluxuries Hair Perfume (alcohol free)

FINE HAIR:
• @detoxie.life Hard Water Shampoo
• @ashbabotanics Conditioner
• @fiixmycurls Leave In Cream
• @ashbabotanics Curl Defining Gel
• @simrasaluxuries Hair Perfume (alcohol free)

Coarse hair has bigger diameter of strand. You can feel it by rolling between fingers. Fine hair is opposite ofcourse and thus gets weighed down fairly easily. Also, coarse hair is extra dry and stubborn.

1. SHAMPOO
•COARSE - A gentle conditioning shampoo will avoid over-stripping of natural oils. Avoid shampoos that leave hair feeling squeaky upon rinsing.
•FINE - A gentle but non-conditioning shampoo will cleanse without leaving hair limp.

2. CONDITIONER AND DETANGLE
•COARSE - Deep conditioners soften and penetrate these layers effectively. Using a heat cap helps elevate the whole experience. Conditioners might not be enough to soften hair. 
•FINE - May turn limp and lifeless if over softened. Conditioners and short-duration-contact work better. Good slip is a must as fine hair can get very tangled.

3. MOISTURISE
•COARSE - This is a MUST! Enjoys all protection and moisture just like very dry skin!
TIP: Use lots of water during styling to help it hydrate and clump well

•FINE - Light weight leave in/cream sparingly helps moisturising hair without weighing down. Little amount of protein will help with bounce.
TIP: Use less water for styling. Water weight might result in less volume

4. STYLING GEL
This is important for both! Hair gels adds shine, holds up the curls shape for days with less frizz.
Avoid drying hair gels for coarse hair. Fine hair can use non drying gels like @ashbabotanics Gels without cream/leave in.

latestPosts.caption:
STOP IT RIGHT NOW🤧🛑

I have seen atleast hundred videos of spraying water on hair and showing such droplets saying its low porosity hair AND THEN providing solution to it? WHY? Why are we looking for solution to something thats not a problem?

FACT1: if we are talking science let’s also consider that water also has surface tension this causing it to form droplets until disturb by hand.

FACT2: Porosity indicates damage level of hair. Healthy hair is low porosity and therefore healthy hair is water resistant! The tight curicles resembling shingles of roof behave as security guards and don’t allow water to enter hair.

FACT3: Water droplets form on hair not just because of tight cuticles (low porosity) but also F layer. There is also Cell Membrane Complex (CMC) that absorbs water quite well and let it in. Basically hair structure is more complex than just spraying hair with water or float test

FACT4: Porosity is not ONE label. New hair is healthy hence low porosity around roots and then increases towards the ends - somewhat medium around mid lengths and higher porosity around ends because they are oldest. This is exactly why ends dry quickly and also splits.

FACT5: Water isn’t bad for hair. It allows hair products to spread better, detangle better, froth better, hair form shapes better. It’s only when hair stays wet everyday for long durations it’s not a great thing.

FACT6: Hair feeling weighed down and limp easily is a sign of fine/thin hair strands and not porosity. Work in the right direction and save moniesss

FACT7: dont buy products according to porosity? Why? Read Fact1-6 again ❣️

Part1 - detangling and sectioning before product application. Watch and save both parts to avoid making tiny tiny mistakes

FOR WAVY HAIR - This will work for both wavy and curly hair - infact if you have wavy hair you don’t have to be so precisely while making clumps so you are good there but rest can be all same. Curly hair is super frizzy and tangly hence so much effort

FOR FINE HAIR: You can follow same routine irrespective of your curl pattern but put less quantity of stylers OR just one styler as fine hair can weigh down easily (i have medium strand width) 

FOR COARSE HAIR: Irrespective of your curl pattern, you can follow same styling technique but add more water while styling else curls might not clumps well. Also you might need more quantity of styling product - play around with it ♥️ (I have medium strand width)

RED HAIR COLOR Things I wish I knew 🫠

1- Red bleeds - All vibrant colours like red blue green purple bleed with every wash. I knew this but wasn’t aware the bleeding would be this intense 😳
2- Transfers on literally EVERYTHING! More while its wet and less while its dry but more or less it transfers onto everything that comes in contact with red hair🤪
3- Fades into orange - Though I requested my colourist to go for a colour that wont fade into orange (dont know if thats possible), it did fade into red - orange. Not complaining because I really like this ‘Auburn’ shade I have been getting for free 😜 but I wish red lasted longer than 1.5 months. Faded quicker than I expected.

That being said, I will get red again😋 Already purchased one from @streaxindia
